ChatGPT said:

For a nested to-do app in MongoDB, you have a few options, but the best choice depends on how you plan to query and update tasks. Here are the two most common approaches:

1. Parent-Child References (Easier & More Flexible)

  • Each task stores a parentTaskId, referencing its parent task.

  • Root tasks have parentTaskId: null.

  • Queries are straightforward, but retrieving deep hierarchies requires multiple queries or aggregation.

Example Schema:

json
{
  "_id": "task1",
  "title": "Main Task",
  "parentTaskId": null,
  "subTasks": ["task2", "task3"],
  "completed": false
},
{
  "_id": "task2",
  "title": "Subtask 1",
  "parentTaskId": "task1",
  "subTasks": [],
  "completed": false
}

✅ Pros:

  • Easier to update tasks (just update the parentTaskId).

  • Simple structure, works well with Mongoose's populate().

  • Scales well for many tasks.

❌ Cons:

  • Fetching deeply nested tasks requires multiple queries or aggregation.

  • Not ideal for deeply nested structures if you need all children in one go.

2. Nested Array (Better for Read Performance)

  • Each task stores its sub-tasks as an embedded array.

  • Works well for small to medium-sized trees but gets tricky when updating deeply nested tasks.

Example Schema:

json
{
  "_id": "task1",
  "title": "Main Task",
  "subTasks": [
    {
      "_id": "task2",
      "title": "Subtask 1",
      "subTasks": []
    }
  ],
  "completed": false
}

✅ Pros:

  • Fast to retrieve an entire task tree in one query.

  • No need for multiple queries when loading nested tasks.

❌ Cons:

  • Updating deep tasks requires modifying an entire document.

  • If the structure gets too large, MongoDB’s document size limit (16MB) could be an issue.

Which One Should You Use?

  • If you expect deep nesting (many levels), go with the Parent-Child model.

  • If you need fast reads and shallow nesting (few levels), the Nested Array model works well.

For a balance between flexibility and performance, I’d recommend the Parent-Child model. It’s easier to manage, and you can always use recursive queries to fetch the entire tree when needed.

What do you think? Would you prefer easier updates or faster reads?

Got it! Since we're using the Nested Array model, here's a clean Mongoose schema for both Tasks and Users.

User Schema (User.js)

Each user can have multiple task lists.

javascript
import mongoose from "mongoose";

const UserSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  username: { type: String, required: true, unique: true },
  email: { type: String, required: true, unique: true },
  password: { type: String, required: true }, // Hashed password
  tasks: [{ type: mongoose.Schema.Types.ObjectId, ref: "Task" }] // References root tasks
}, { timestamps: true });

export default mongoose.model("User", UserSchema);

Task Schema (Task.js)

This supports deeply nested subtasks.

javascript
import mongoose from "mongoose";

const TaskSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  title: { type: String, required: true },
  description: { type: String },
  completed: { type: Boolean, default: false },
  subTasks: [
    {
      title: { type: String, required: true },
      description: { type: String },
      completed: { type: Boolean, default: false },
      subTasks: [] // Recursively allows nesting
    }
  ],
  user: { type: mongoose.Schema.Types.ObjectId, ref: "User", required: true } // Link to the user
}, { timestamps: true });

export default mongoose.model("Task", TaskSchema);

Why This Works Well

✅ Easy Read Operations – Fetch a task and get all subtasks in one query.
✅ Simple Write Operations – Add subtasks directly inside the parent task.
✅ Supports Deep Nesting – MongoDB allows recursive structures.

Got it! Here's the refined Mongoose schema for Users, Collections, and Tasks, following your updated structure.

User Schema (User.js)

Each user has multiple collections.

javascript
import mongoose from "mongoose";

const UserSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  username: { type: String, required: true, unique: true },
  email: { type: String, required: true, unique: true },
  password: { type: String, required: true }, // Hashed password
  collections: [{ type: mongoose.Schema.Types.ObjectId, ref: "Collection" }], // References user's collections
}, { timestamps: true });

export default mongoose.model("User", UserSchema);

Collection Schema (Collection.js)

Each collection belongs to a user and contains tasks.

javascript
import mongoose from "mongoose";

const CollectionSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  name: { type: String, required: true },
  isFavorite: { type: Boolean, default: false }, // User can mark favorite collections
  dueDate: { type: Date, default: null }, // Optional due date for the collection
  tasks: [{ type: mongoose.Schema.Types.ObjectId, ref: "Task" }], // List of tasks inside the collection
  user: { type: mongoose.Schema.Types.ObjectId, ref: "User", required: true } // Link to the owner
}, { timestamps: true });

export default mongoose.model("Collection", CollectionSchema);

Task Schema (Task.js)

Tasks can be nested inside collections.

javascript
import mongoose from "mongoose";

const TaskSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  title: { type: String, required: true },
  description: { type: String },
  completed: { type: Boolean, default: false },
  priority: { type: String, enum: ["low", "medium", "high"], default: "medium" }, // Task priority
  dueDate: { type: Date, default: null }, // Optional due date for individual tasks
  subTasks: [
    {
      title: { type: String, required: true },
      description: { type: String },
      completed: { type: Boolean, default: false },
      subTasks: [] // Supports infinite nesting
    }
  ],
  collection: { type: mongoose.Schema.Types.ObjectId, ref: "Collection", required: true } // Belongs to a collection
}, { timestamps: true });

export default mongoose.model("Task", TaskSchema);

How This Works

✅ Users own multiple Collections.
✅ Each Collection contains Tasks.
✅ Tasks support nested subtasks.
✅ Due dates can be set for both Collections and Tasks.
✅ Priority added for task importance.

1️⃣ Collection Model (models/Collection.ts)

First, update the Collection model to match your existing Account structure.

typescript
import { Schema, model, Document } from "mongoose";

interface ICollection extends Document {
  name: string;
  isFavorite: boolean;
  dueDate?: Date;
  tasks: string[]; // References Task IDs
  account: string; // References the Account model
}

const CollectionSchema = new Schema<ICollection>(
  {
    name: { type: String, required: true },
    isFavorite: { type: Boolean, default: false },
    dueDate: { type: Date, default: null },
    tasks: [{ type: Schema.Types.ObjectId, ref: "Task" }],
    account: { type: Schema.Types.ObjectId, ref: "Account", required: true },
  },
  { timestamps: true }
);

export default model<ICollection>("Collection", CollectionSchema);

2️⃣ Collection Controller (controllers/collectionController.ts)

Handles CRUD operations for collections.

typescript
import { Request, Response } from "express";
import Collection from "../models/Collection";

/**
 * @desc    Create a new collection
 * @route   POST /api/collections
 * @access  Private
 */
export const createCollection = async (req: Request, res: Response) => {
  try {
    const { name, dueDate } = req.body;
    const accountId = req.user.id; // Assuming `req.user` is set from auth middleware

    if (!name) {
      return res.status(400).json({ message: "Collection name is required" });
    }

    const newCollection = new Collection({
      name,
      dueDate,
      account: accountId,
    });

    await newCollection.save();
    return res.status(201).json(newCollection);
  } catch (error) {
    return res.status(500).json({ message: "Server Error", error });
  }
};

/**
 * @desc    Get all collections for a user
 * @route   GET /api/collections
 * @access  Private
 */
export const getCollections = async (req: Request, res: Response) => {
  try {
    const accountId = req.user.id;

    const collections = await Collection.find({ account: accountId }).populate("tasks");
    return res.status(200).json(collections);
  } catch (error) {
    return res.status(500).json({ message: "Server Error", error });
  }
};

/**
 * @desc    Update a collection
 * @route   PATCH /api/collections/:id
 * @access  Private
 */
export const updateCollection = async (req: Request, res: Response) => {
  try {
    const { name, isFavorite, dueDate } = req.body;
    const accountId = req.user.id;
    const collectionId = req.params.id;

    const collection = await Collection.findOne({ _id: collectionId, account: accountId });

    if (!collection) {
      return res.status(404).json({ message: "Collection not found" });
    }

    if (name) collection.name = name;
    if (isFavorite !== undefined) collection.isFavorite = isFavorite;
    if (dueDate) collection.dueDate = dueDate;

    await collection.save();
    return res.status(200).json(collection);
  } catch (error) {
    return res.status(500).json({ message: "Server Error", error });
  }
};

/**
 * @desc    Delete a collection
 * @route   DELETE /api/collections/:id
 * @access  Private
 */
export const deleteCollection = async (req: Request, res: Response) => {
  try {
    const accountId = req.user.id;
    const collectionId = req.params.id;

    const collection = await Collection.findOneAndDelete({ _id: collectionId, account: accountId });

    if (!collection) {
      return res.status(404).json({ message: "Collection not found" });
    }

    return res.status(200).json({ message: "Collection deleted successfully" });
  } catch (error) {
    return res.status(500).json({ message: "Server Error", error });
  }
};

3️⃣ Collection Routes (routes/collectionRoutes.ts)

Set up the API routes for collections.

typescript
import express from "express";
import { createCollection, getCollections, updateCollection, deleteCollection } from "../controllers/collectionController";
import authMiddleware from "../middleware/authMiddleware"; // Ensure the user is authenticated

const router = express.Router();

router.post("/", authMiddleware, createCollection);
router.get("/", authMiddleware, getCollections);
router.patch("/:id", authMiddleware, updateCollection);
router.delete("/:id", authMiddleware, deleteCollection);

export default router;

4️⃣ Register Routes in server.ts

Ensure your server is using the new routes.

typescript
import express from "express";
import collectionRoutes from "./routes/collectionRoutes";

const app = express();

app.use(express.json());
app.use("/api/collections", collectionRoutes);

export default app;

  • Get user’s collections (GET /api/collections)

  • Update collection details (PATCH /api/collections/:id)

  • Delete a collection (DELETE /api/collections/:id)
